sec.p:
An ENA is formed when a fast ion (in this paper usually a proton with an energy between 10 eV and 6 keV) exchanges its charge with an ambient neutral atom (in this paper usually neutral hydrogen). The ENA then leaves its place of origin with almost the same momentum as the parent ion on a straight trajectory and can reach an ENA instrument far away. The detected ENA intensity can be written as the line-of-sight integral over the local proton intensity jp\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
